Sorrell sees off a shareholder revolt over his £43million pay: Advertising tycoon allowed to keep pay deal that allows him £274,000 a year so wife can join him on business trips 
Sir Martin Sorrell's annual pay includes perk for his second, younger wifeThe allowance has been branded as 'ridiculous' and 'odd' by his critics He also gets £50,000 a year to stay in his own homes while on businessSir Martin 'looks a bit grubby and ridiculous with these payments'  By

Louise Eccles


and 
Rupert Steiner for the Daily Mail


Published:
  18:15 EDT, 9 June 2015

 | 
Updated:
  18:42 EDT, 9 June 2015














e-mail








10
shares

 
          25
View  comments



  





 Sir Martin Sorrell has been allowed to keep his £43million package, which includes £274,000 to fly wife Lady Cristiana Falcone-Sorrell around the worldBritain's highest paid FTSE 100 boss has been allowed to keep his £43million pay package – including £274,000 to fly his wife around the world.Sir Martin Sorrell’s exorbitant pay package includes the perk for his second wife, Lady Cristiana Falcone-Sorrell, to accompany him on business trips.The perk was branded ‘ridiculous’ and ‘odd’, as critics questioned whether the advertising tycoon needed an allowance for his wife on top of his bumper pay package.Italian-born Lady Cristiana, who is almost 30 years younger than her 70-year-old husband, accompanies him on trips in between carrying out her own role with the World Economic Forum in Switzerland.Sir Martin, the chief executive of the world’s largest advertising agency WPP, is also paid £50,000 a year to stay in his own homes, including his New York flat, while on business, on the premise this saves the company money on hotel bills.Yesterday, almost a quarter of investors refused to back the enormous £43million annual pay packet at an annual shareholders’ meeting, but were over-ruled by the majority.Some shareholders argued that the pay was ‘more than enough’ and criticised the chief executive for all the add-on perks included in his package.But Sir Martin, who lives with his wife in a grand four-storey townhouse in Knightsbridge, has argued he is worth the money.Addressing his performance head-on at the annual meeting in central London, the chief executive said any shareholder who invested £1,000 pounds 20 years ago would now have a holding worth £15,800.But Luke Hildyard, of the High Pay Centre, said: ‘If Sorrell was paid a more sensible, proportionate amount of money, he would be more famous for his undoubted business prowess than for his ludicrous pay packages.  





 Sir Martin has argued that he is worth the money - but one critic said his salary made him 'look a bit grubby'‘Instead he makes himself look a bit grubby and ridiculous with these payments.‘It’s hard to fathom the thought process of someone who is paid £43 million but still wants to weasel money out of his company to pay for his wife’s trips abroad.‘Ordinary people, whose employers mostly don’t pay for their spouse to accompany them to work, might find this a little odd.’


