Roger Jeary, a trustee of ShareAction, said yesterday: ‘I am concerned that this remuneration package does not offer value for shareholders.’But another private shareholder called Mr Hudson, speaking at the annual meeting, said: ‘Martin is worth every penny.’Sir Martin, who built up WPP from nothing in 1986 into one of Britain’s best known companies, has clashed repeatedly with investors over his pay in the past few years.  





 Sir Martin has clashed repeatedly with investors over the amount he is paid in the past few yearsBut the number of investors objecting has decreased over time. Nearly 60 percent of shareholders rejected his pay package in 2012, compared to 30 percent last year and 22 per cent this year.Ashley Hamilton Claxton, at shareholder Royal London Asset Management, said: ‘There is no doubt that Martin Sorrell is a successful CEO who has created value for shareholders, but sometimes investors need to ask themselves ‘when is enough, enough?’.‘In our view, £43million is more than enough.’Guy Jubb, of Standard Life, who opposed the pay reward, said: ‘We have been concerned for some time by the perception that Sir Martin has the potential to dominate the board’s decision taking.’Sir Martin’s 2005 divorce from his first wife Sandra cost him £29.3million.During the divorce hearing, it was claimed that his business interests took him away from home for weeks at a time, apparently placing a strain on their marriage.American-born Lady Sorrell said she felt ‘marginalised and dehumanised’ as he threw himself into his career. She claimed his obsession with work was the reason for the marriage breaking down in 2003.Sir Martin has donated millions of pounds to his charitable foundation over the years, which supports cancer research.



