  The new challenge of Sir Martin Sorrell
 With the acquisition of Grey, WPP would become the world's largest advertising groups. But he will have to live two rivals Unilever and Procter & Gamble.
Sir Martin has struck again. The greatest predator the world of advertising, Martin Sorrell, CEO of WPP, has just afford the seventh group of global industry: Grey. A transaction valued at 1.31 billion, or nearly once the U.S. group's revenues, which totaled $ 1.43 billion in 2003. A ratio well below that of other transactions of this kind. To acquire Bcom3 in 2002, Publicis had paid 1.6 times the earnings of the holding company of Leo Burnett and D'Arcy.
So a new trophy hanging on the hunting board already full, the CEO of WPP, which has successively set his sights on J. Walter Thompson (1987), Ogilvy & Mather (1989) and Young & Rubicam (2000), as well Tempus in 2001. Ironically, on the case as then Grey on Tempus WPP takes all ahead in Havas. Candidate to buy the network Ed Meyer, the group chaired by Alain de Pouzilhac did not want to out-bid by WPP (see sidebar).
With this acquisition, WPP donning a short head Omnicom based on 2003 revenue (8.637 billion dollars with Grey, against 8.621 billion). More important, the boss of WPP acquires a fourth global network. A new offer on the market. But this solution was probably imposed to manage the main budget Grey, representing over 10% of its revenues: Procter & Gamble. Martin Sorrell will have to demonstrate that they can coexist within the same group two rivals also demanding that P & G and Unilever (client history of J. Walter Thompson). Publicis, another major partner of P & G, a prospective time in the race to buy Grey, will not pray out of the woodwork at the slightest problem. Conversely, P & G has perhaps no interest in putting all your eggs in one basket.
Martin Sorrell has also promised to increase the operating margin of Grey, particularly low in relation to market standards. An objective requiring radical methods that could cringe at Grey. Ed Meyer, seventy-seven years, will remain in effect at the head of the group until late 2006. That's enough to fill the remaining months of Martin Sorrell, whose strategy seems to boil down to a mad race for acquisitions. Twenty years after Saatchi, ephemeral world number one and was its finance director, Sir Martin was clearly a revenge.
