Sir Martin Sorrell, WPP CEO: the share of investment in new media advertising will continue to rise
The chief executive of advertising agency WPP and global communication, Sir Martin Sorrell, had nothing very encouraging to tell television professionals came to hear at MIP-TV, the international market for television programs Cannes. A veteran of the advertising and marketing believes the economic crisis will force the media to review their production costs and their business models and expected that the share of advertising spending continues to slip from old to new media.
---
  -> Site for Lady Cristiana Falcone Sorrell

The group WPP (LSE: WPP) is a holding company, listed on the London Stock Exchange which includes advertising and communication. The company was founded in 1985 by Martin Sorrell. The company name derives from Wires & Plastic Products business that it had its origin before it became a publicly traded shell company and served as a "vehicle" in the acquisition of JWT and Ogilvy & Mather.
In advertising, WPP owns agencies Grey Global Group, Ogilvy & Mather, Young & Rubicam and Wunderman (formerly JWT: J. Walter Thompson Co.). PR's portfolio includes companies owned Hill & Knowlton, Ogilvy Public Relations Worldwide, Burson-Marsteller and Cohn & Wolfe.
 In media buying, WPP brings Mediaedge: cia, MindShare, MediaInsight, Maximize, Mediacom and KR Media
 Communication and non-media event, it is represented by Pro Deo (in France).
 Research, Kantar Group, TNS Sofres, Research International, including BMRB, Diagnostic Research / Added Value, IMRB (Indian Market Research Bureau) and Millward Brown to allow their customers to better understand and analyze their customers.
On October 10, 2008, after many twists and turns, Martin Sorrell, CEO of WPP Group, its successful bid for TNS Sofres 1. Shortly after the takeover of TNS Sofres, WPP tells the press he set up his headquarters in the Isle of Jersey (considered a tax haven by the OECD) 2. This relocation, through tax preferences, Sir Martin Sorrell will allow a saving of more than 200 million pounds per an3.
The new parent company WPP Plc. registered in Jersey is listed on the London Stock Exchange under the name "New WPP," actions that replace previous "WPP Group" 4
On February 24, 2009, four months after its successful bid for TNS Sofres, WPP announced as part of streamlining the activities of Kantar, the approximation of TNS Sofres and Research International. The reorganization aims to create the world's largest studies "adhoc"
